		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston</placeName>&#44; <date>July 11<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1852</date></p>
			<p>My dear Sir&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Your esteemed favor I recd some time ago<lb/> but having nothing of importance to communicate I<lb/> delayed until I recd Amt of your Bill against KKBE.<lb/> which had been ordered for payment last month&#59; &#8212;I shall<lb/> enclose it with amt due for Binding &#38;c.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I saw <persName>Rev M Myer</persName> yesterday and delivered your message<lb/> respecting the article in the Phillippson paper. <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi> Myer</persName> requested<lb/> me to state that he is <hi rend="underline">not the author</hi> of the Article in question<lb/> nor does he know who is&#44; he intends to write you on the<lb/> Subject. I <del>notice</del> observe that you have noticed this attack<lb/> in the <add>&#63;</add> of the Occident. Can you my friend expect<lb/> that your views should meet the approbation of the entire<lb/> public. I wish you would adopt the high and dignified course of allowing<lb/> the little dogs to bark&#8212;with out any regard to their noise.<lb/> I pray you to keep such articles out of your paper as <hi rend="underline">this</hi><lb/> the <hi rend="underline">invitation for the</hi> <sic>anonimous</sic> correspondent of Asmoneon to<lb/> come forward with his name&#44;&#8212;and your correspondents letter<lb/> from <placeName>New York</placeName> about <hi rend="underline">your title of Revd</hi> <del>to Mr who I</del><lb/> What do the public care for these things&#44; and it cannot<lb/> possibly add to your reputation&#59;&#8212;I take the liberty to say<lb/> so much to you only for the purpose of bringing to your mind that<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> the man &#38; his principles must be of some consequence if they<lb/> are publicly attacked&#44; but that you should notice all these attacks<lb/> is as preposterous as it is <sic>unpracticable</sic>&#44; in noticing them you<lb/> make them of consequence. &#40;whether they are so or not&#41;&#8212;<lb/> The sensitive plant&#58; droops and yields to every breath of air&#44; while the Oak resists the tempest.<lb/> blast.&#8212;and&#44; on the morrow appear the fresher and more beautiful from the Encounter</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>may I call your attention to the resolution <add>&#63;</add> I sent you<lb/> by <persName>M Valentine</persName>&#44; <add>&#63;</add> <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. E</persName> to lecture&#44; and the action of<lb/> the meeting <del>thereupon</del> on <persName>Lyons</persName> resignation&#44; its publication would<lb/> benefit our friend <persName>Eckman</persName> more especially as the report<lb/> is current in <placeName>N Y.</placeName> that <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. E</persName> was the cause of <persName>Lyons</persName> resig<lb/>nation&#44; the resolutions are public property and are officially<lb/> sent to you. &#40;the remarks of <persName>Valentine</persName> you can omit if you<lb/> think proper. Merely state the reason for <persName>Lyons</persName> resigning that<lb/> the world may know the true cause. You also omitted<lb/> to publish the <del>letter of</del> circular of the Members of KKBE<lb/> &#40;which I furnished you&#41;. Signed by a large number of friends<lb/> of <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. E.</persName> approving his course on resigning&#41; the publication of this would<lb/> have done <persName>D<hi rend="sup">r</hi>. E</persName> some permanent good. I suppose you have<lb/> overlooked it. I have been asked by very many of the<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> why you hesitated to publish it&#44; <hi rend="underline">after promising me</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">that you would</hi>&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I am highly delighted with your thoughts on the Jewish<lb/> Ministry. I rejoice that you have come out <hi rend="underline">so boldly</hi><lb/> and denounced the present mode of <hi rend="underline">acting</hi> in our<lb/> synagogue in your <hi rend="underline">next</hi> tell them something about praying<lb/> in the language they understand&#44; those who do not understand<lb/> the Hebrew and make a believe they pray in it because they recite them there prayers are of no use.<lb/> Advocate a portion of the prayers to be read in English<lb/> viz <hi rend="underline">the <add>&#63;</add></hi> and then afterwards in Hebrew&#8212;and<lb/> the same with several others&#44; so that the <hi rend="underline">people</hi> may<lb/> understand some of the service. Where lip service is an<lb/> abomination&#44; Now is the time to promulgate the<lb/> truth to the people.</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>I have recd <hi rend="underline">an invitation</hi> to the <hi rend="underline">wedding</hi> of our mutual<lb/> friend <persName>S. Solis</persName>&#8212;this event so unlooked for and so sudden<lb/> took me rather by <sic>surprize</sic>. I trust he has acted with<lb/> his usual forethought and excellent <sic>judgement</sic>&#44; in this<lb/> matter.  &#8220;I hope the end will justify the means&#44;&#8221; for fear<lb/> this remark may be misconstrued I explain it thus&#58; I hope<lb/> marriage may be the means of prolonging his life and restoring<lb/> his health&#44; amen&#44; have you had time to think of this affair&#63;<lb/>  give me your views of his health when he returns&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear <persName>Sarah</persName> has been quite indisposed she desires her kind regards.<lb/> the children are well.</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)">Yours sincerely</p>
          <p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">J. N. Carvalho</persName></p>
			<p><addressee>Rev I Leeser</addressee>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Phil<hi rend="sup">a</hi></placeName></p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p>Editor Occident</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Walnut St. near Thirteenth</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>.</p>
          
